<br>
Many years ago, I was on a family holiday in southwest France. We rented a cottage in this rather remote area. The view from the back of the cottage was really quite spectacular. We were looking down this long gorge that disappeared into the distance. About half a mile away a rocky headland jutted out from one side.<br>
<br>
(Now we get to the good bit)<br>
<br>
Right on the tip of this headland, just where the sun went down every night, there was sited, in true Gallic “I’ll do whatever I want and sod what you think” style, an electricity transmission tower!<br>
<br>
Not one of those rather graceful British ones that tapers up into the sky either! Oh no, this was one of those  “I’m a bloody great transmission tower and I want the whole world to know it” type of tower! The sort you tend to see in the USA.<br>
<br>
I am sure that there must have been lots of technical reasons for siteing this tower in this particular location, and I dare say that aesthetics wasn’t particularly high up on the list.<br>
<br>
However, as the sun set each evening, as it descended through the latticework of steel and cables, the effect was truly stunning. This was a real work of art!<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Now, it has to be said, I couldn’t see any other towers. The cables appeared out of nowhere on one side and disappeared from view on the other. I dare say that if a whole string of towers had been in view the effect would have been less attractive. But it does go to show that the products of human industry do not always have to be eyesores! And it is wrong to, as a matter of principle, assume that they will always be so (as so many refusniks seem to do)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smokin --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smokin.gif ALT=":smokin"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Dusty<br>
